d "non-attitudes," but Longoria suggests it would be better to call them "bi-attitudes." When people have internalized the contradictions and believe in both¬ ideas even when the two are incompatible, they are being transconsistent rather than inconsistent. Transconsistency, Longoria concludes, leads to perpetual dissatisfaction with the political system because the government often attempts to satisfy the incompatible preferences of a two-faced public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical culturezUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPolitical psychologyzUnited States. 0aPublic opinionzUnited States. 4aPhilosophy : Pragmatism. 4aPolitics and Law : American Politics. 4aPolitics and Law : Democracy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Behavior. 4aPublic Policy : Public Opinion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438472423423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438472423/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles